Question: What's your best tip to thrive as an SMU student?
Comment: Edited · 24w
Uni will pass by quickly 🥲.. so cherish those moments with your close friends and always try something new. Uni is the best time to try, fail, reflect and cherish 🌸🌟
Be open minded and stay consistent :)
Be consistent in everything, revision, projects, meetings
be consistent and resilient in everything you do! push through and have breaks in between!
be grateful that you're receiving education in a uni and remember how hard you've worked to get here!
Be positive when facing any problems 😊
Try new activities and you might just find something new that you like! Take breaks and chill with friends
do not wait until the last minute to study for exams🔥 stay focused in class and try to clarify any doubts with prof📚
trust in ur abilities! and don't procrastinate too too much :)

my biggest tip is actually to join a cca!! I think having a strong support/ community is rly important and enriching as a student, PLUS you get to do something that you love/ enjoy while being around a supportive community of friends that also know what youre gg thru in sch :)
take breaks and walk around sch / libraries when u can ! a little breather and stretching of your muscles can go a long way ❤️❤️🌱
Having a supportive community rooting for you!
Take breaks!!! And surround yourself with people that spark joy in your life okie? Your uni life is too short to be surrounded by people who drain you! ❤️
Don't be afraid to rely on ur support systems (friends, family, profs and counsellors etc), YOU'RE NEVER ALONE 🙌
build a network of support to get you through tough times!
when things get overwhelming, get a braek drink and sit by campus green and chill ☺️
Consistency (be it in revision or sleep) - having a routine helps to get the engine going on tough days

Remember to always have a balance, don’t feel pressured to study for longer hours/pull an all-nighter because it could be less effective in the long run. Always listen to your own needs,, and don’t give up :))!
Remember that uni is a marathon, not a sprint: don't overwork yourself, don't get complacent if you do well for one sem and don't give up if you dont do well as there is time to turn things around!
Always take breaks and take care of yourself during the semester!
stay optimistic and take frequent breaks!
Realising that SMU has many support systems! And using them to create a support system!
Meditate! Helps to clear mind and regain inner strength.
don’t be overly focused on grades, try to gain work experience and expand your professional network!!
join a community (e.g. cca)! it add colours to your university life :)
run your own race at your own pace, don’t compare!

cultivate a mindset of consistency over perfection. It's easy to get overwhelmed by the pressure to be perfect in every assignment or exam, but progress comes from consistent effort, not from always getting everything right.

Course results are important in school, while results isn’t deterministic in your life journey ahead, do what you can with your best efforts and within your means, take care of your mental health and don’t cram study materials for the sake of it, go for understanding and you’ll better remember things naturally as it slowly gets all interconnected, step outside your comfort zone to join networking and club/social activities, more often than not by doing so you may find yourself in a better position than achieving As for your modules
Don't just work hard, work smart! Tap on all the different resources the school has like the libraries, online tools like chatgpt, turnitin and even tips and tricks from friends and profs!
make new friends as they can help and support you whenever you are feeling down! and to consult prof if there's any doubt!
grass is always greener on the other side, being content is important
Overbid is better than underbid especially when there are few slots left
take a deep breath when stressed 🔥

Find what works for you! Don’t be afraid to study/attend classes in your own “style”, even though it may not be the conventional “style”. Everyone is different so what works for others may not work for you, and what works for you may not work for others! Forcing yourself to conform would be stressful so just be you and do it your way!
be open-minded and try your best to make friends and new experiences 🔥 speak up often and ask questions whenever possible to consolidate your learning ❤️

Question: Comment a budgeting, saving or any other money management hack!
Comment: Edited · 39w

always on a lookout for special student promotions esp for dining ! because food category is my biggest percentage of expenditure each month, hence whenever I can I would make sure I cut down my costs in that area 🥳🙌🏻 (p.s. smu pls lower food prices😢)

Keeping a spreadsheet of expenses and calculating your "Cost of Living" (a monthly tracker is a good start!) is a great way to see your financial profile! From this, you can understand more about yourself, and when coupled with a list of needs and wants, you can portion out your finances accordingly and figure out where to cut or delegate! I also love thinking about how much happiness an item will bring me, and what its probable future in my life is HAHA
Think if its a need or a want before purchasing
Consider for a few days before buying something expensive
Feed your needs, but if there's something you have to procrastinate on it's your wants 😂
Always search for cheaper alternatives before buying something
Create a 48 hour rule: wait for 48 hours before making a non-essential purchase to prevent impulsive buying.
keep track of your expenses for a month and see how much you truly spend (since we tend to underestimate things)
instead of eating out which can be expensive with GST and service charges, try to cook your own meals, or eat with your family with some good home cooked food!!

When doing online shopping, I put the items I want in the cart first. If I find myself coming back to look at it again multiple times, that is when I know I really want it (bc if I forget about it, it means I do not exactly want or need it)
If there’s anything you want to buy, sleep on it for a night and then ponder over it again to avoid impulse purchases
Be honest with yourself on how much you’re spending, no one is judging you :)
tracking your expenses in a spreadsheet

Keep a simple financial tracker. This could be a money app, or for my case, an excel sheet. This allows you to have a view of how much you are spending, where you are spending it on (i.e. food, transport, leisure) and enables you to make informed decision about spending based on a monthly budget (Should you cut back? Do you have excess to splurge?)
cooking your own meals instead of eating out!

Capitalise on the eighth wonder of the world - Compound Interest (it’s not about timing the market to put your capital, but amount of time your capital is in the market)

First of all you need to have a clear understanding of what you have, including but not limited to money, clothes, makeup, etc. Only then when you are purchasing a new item can you better judge whether you need this new item or not, thus avoiding wastage. Secondly never overspend, if you don’t have enough money to buy current items then don‘t buy them, don’t overspend your future. Finally, try to use up every last drop of value of an item and don‘t buy a new item to replace it until you have used it up.
